<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-040-285 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 373 865</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 2 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Weather Channel buys Amex's &quot;900&quot; exchange. (American ExpressTravel Related Services' 900-WEATHER service purchased by cabletelevision network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Weather Channel Inc. (Acquisitions, mergers, divestments)American Express Travel Related Services Company Inc.andO;(Acquisitions, mergers, divestments).andO;Topic:     AcquisitionAudiotexCommunications Service SuppliersCable TV.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Weather Channel Buys Amex's &quot;900&quot; Exchange 10/02/91 ATLANTA, GEORGIA, U.S.A.,andO;1991 OCT 2 (NB) -- The Weather Channel has bought out its competition in anattempt to dominate the market for weather advice delivered over &quot;900&quot;numbers.andM;Despite recent moves by the FCC and two large service bureaus to restrict theexchange, many in the industry think that &quot;900&quot; pay-per-call services nowhave new life, if they are priced low and sponsored by reputable companies.andM;This spelled opportunity for The Weather Channel, which bought out  AmericanExpress Travel Related Services' 900-WEATHER, which had been the mostwidely-used such number.andP;  The Weather Channel will now put its name on thenumber, and charge 95 cents per minute for calls.andP;  The number will also nowbe served by WestInteractive at the 900-WEATHER number.andM;Paul A. FitzPatrick, the Weather Channel president, noted in a press releasethat the service will now cover more than 900 cities, with more detail andspecialized reports than before.andP;  The new number will also &quot;increase thepervasiveness of the Weather Channel brand,&quot; he said.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19911002/Press Contact: Jerry Glover, Weather Channel,404-434-6800)</TEXT></DOC>